{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"38d7a8cb-5b07-4312-8ec4-a815c42d9c9c","content":"Here's my analysis:\n\n## Root Cause\n\nThe project and code are fine — the `.csproj` is minimal and the project compiles in <500ms as noted. The 2–4 second overhead comes from **MSBuild process startup and project re-evaluation** on every `dotnet build` invocation. Visual Studio avoids this because it keeps a **long-lived MSBuild server process** in memory.\n\n## Recommendations\n\n### 1. Enable the MSBuild Build Server (biggest win)\n\nSet this environment variable to keep a persistent MSBuild node between builds, mirroring what VS does:\n\n```bash\nexport DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1\n```\n\nAdd it to your shell profile (`.bashrc`, `.zshrc`, etc.) so it persists. This eliminates the cold-start project graph evaluation on every build.\n\n### 2. Use `dotnet watch` for the inner loop\n\nFor edit→build→run cycles, use:\n\n```bash\ndotnet watch run          # rebuilds + runs on file changes\ndotnet watch build        # rebuilds only on file changes\n```\n\nThis keeps the build process alive, watches for changes, and triggers fast incremental rebuilds — no startup cost after the first build.\n\n### 3. Use `--no-restore` when iterating\n\nIf packages haven't changed, skip the restore check:\n\n```bash\ndotnet build --no-restore\n```\n\nThis shaves off the NuGet resolution step on each invocation.\n\n---\n\n**Summary:** The project itself isn't the problem — the overhead is purely CLI process startup. The MSBuild server (`DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1`) and `dotnet watch` are the two highest-impact changes for matching VS-like incremental build speed on the command line.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"6f23bea8-fdd2-463f-b3a8-bb3095f08768","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The developer reports that `dotnet build` from the CLI is slow for incremental builds (2-4 seconds even when nothing changed), while Visual Studio builds almost instantly.\n\nThe key insight here is about **why** Visual Studio is faster: VS uses a long-lived MSBuild server process that keeps the project graph loaded in memory, avoiding the startup and re-evaluation cost on each build. The CLI, by default, starts a new MSBuild process each time.\n\nThe solution is to use the **MSBuild Build Server** (also known as `dotnet build-server` or the MSBuild server). Starting with .NET 8, there's built-in support for keeping a long-lived MSBuild worker process via:\n\n\n- **`dotnet watch`** — keeps the build process running and watches for file changes, rebuilding only when needed. This avoids the startup cost entirely.\n- **The MSBuild Build Server** — In .NET 8+, there's built-in support for a persistent build server that reuses the MSBuild process across invocations, similar to how Visual Studio works. can enable it with an environment variable to keep MSBuild nodes alive between builds, similar to how Visual Studio works. I should also mention `dotnet watch` for file-watching-based incremental rebuilds, and potentially graph-based builds for parallelization. The MSBuild server approach seems like the most direct recommendation for improving build performance in this scenario. The project structure itself is solid, so the real bottleneck is just the CLI startup overhead. I should focus on the environment variable to enable the MSBuild server, recommend `dotnet watch build` for faster iteration, and mention that a `Directory.Build.props` file could add additional performance tweaks if needed.","outputTokens":1452,"requestId":"D80C:3B680:6DDAE2C:7622672:6A03CC71"},"id":"d94d1f69-1a8e-4828-942e-2c078682e2d0","timestamp":"2026-05-13T00:57:52.274Z","parentId":"53f10ab1-38f8-46c6-bc9d-c863b1918e44"}
